[Unrelated arthropod-borne viruses are responsible for Rift Valley fever and
West Nile Fever. Rift Valley fever virus is classified as a member of the
genus _Phlebovirus_ of the family _Bunyaviridae_, whereas West Nile virus
belongs to the genus _Flavivirus_ of the family _Flaviviridae_. West Nile
virus is maintained in a mosquito-bird-mosquito cycle, involving
predominantly _Culex_ spp. mosquitoes, and only rarely causes a fatal
encephalitis in humans. Rift Valley fever virus, on the other hand, is one
of the most important veterinary pathogens, and it has been responsible for
epidemics of severe often haemorrhagic human disease. Apart from the
severity of the associated disease, Rift Valley fever virus is the greater
hazard because it has the potential to be transmitted without the
involvement of an arthropod vector, and also to survive transovarially,in
arthropods. - Mod.CP
